recalls.Component: AIR BAGS: AIR BAG/RESTRAINT CONTROL MODULE
recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2016-2017 911 and Boxster, 2016 Cayman and Panamera vehicles.  The air bag Electronic Control Unit (ECU) may have a defective power supply capacitor that can result in air bag deactivation or inadvertent deployment of the air bags.
recalls.Consequence: Deactivated air bags increase the risk of injury.  Inadvertent deployment of the air bags increase the risk of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Porsche will notify owners, and dealers will install new software and replace the air bag ECU as necessary, free of charge.   Interim notices informing owners of the safety risk were mailed September 13, 2019.  Owners received a second notice and the recall began February 12, 2020.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AKB4.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain model year 2017 718 Boxster, 718 Boxster S, 718 Cayman, 718 Cayman S, 911 Carrera, 911 Carrera S, 911 Carrera S Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4S, 911 Turbo, 911 Turbo S, 911 Carrera 4S Cabriolet, and 911 Turbo Cabriolet vehicles.  The seat mounted side air bag inflator initiator may fail to ignite during a crash.
recalls.Consequence: If the air bag inflator initiator fails to ignite, the side air bag will not deploy, increasing the risk of injury in the event of a crash.
recalls.Remedy: Porsche will notify owners, and dealers will replace the affected air bag modules, free of charge.  The recall began April 2017.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for this recall is AG10.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

recalls.Summary: Porsche Cars North America, Inc. (Porsche) is recalling certain 2017 911 Carrera Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4 Cabriolet, 911 Carrera 4S Cabriolet, 911 Carrera S Cabriolet, 911 Targa S, 911 Targa 4S, 911 Turbo Cabriolet, 718 Boxter and 718 Boxter S vehicles.  During manufacturing, the windshield may not have been properly bonded to the vehicle, allowing it to detach in a crash.  As such, these vehicles fail to comply with the requirements of Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard (FMVSS) number 212, "Windshield Mounting."
recalls.Consequence: In the event of a crash, if the windshield separates from the vehicle, it can increase the risk of injury.
recalls.Remedy: Porsche will notify owners, and dealers will rebond the windshield, free of charge.  The recall began on May 12, 2016.  Owners may contact Porsche customer service at 1-800-767-7243.  Porsche's number for the recall is AH04.
recalls.Notes: Owners may also contact the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration Vehicle Safety Hotline at 1-888-327-4236 (TTY 1-800-424-9153), or go to www.safercar.gov.

issues.title: Weissach Package Magnesium Wheels Cracking
issues.description: Owners with the Weissach Package have reported cracking issues with the lightweight magnesium wheels, particularly around the spoke areas and rim edges. This appears to be related to the material properties of magnesium under stress and thermal cycling.
issues.fix_description: Complete wheel replacement required. Porsche has replaced some wheels under warranty.
issues.prevention: Avoid aggressive curbing, regular wheel inspections, proper torque specifications

issues.title: Engine Mount Failure
issues.description: The engine mounts, particularly the rear engine mount, have been reported to fail prematurely on track-driven GT2 RS models. This is attributed to the extreme forces generated by the high-performance engine and aggressive driving conditions.
symptoms: Engine movement visible during rev matching
issues.fix_description: Replace failed engine mounts with OEM or upgraded aftermarket units
issues.prevention: Regular inspection after track use, avoid excessive wheel spin or launch control abuse

issues.title: Turbocharger Wastegate Rattle
issues.description: A characteristic rattle noise from the turbochargers' wastegate actuators, particularly noticeable during idle and low RPM conditions. While often considered normal, some cases indicate actual mechanical wear.
symptoms: Rattling noise from engine bay at idle
Sound more prominent when engine is warm
issues.fix_description: Turbocharger wastegate actuator replacement or complete turbocharger rebuild
issues.prevention: Regular oil changes, proper warm-up procedures, avoid excessive boost pressure modifications

issues.title: PDK Transmission Overheating
issues.description: During extended track sessions, the PDK transmission can overheat, leading to reduced performance and potential damage. The issue is particularly prevalent in hot weather conditions or on demanding tracks.
issues.fix_description: Install additional transmission cooling, replace transmission fluid, possible transmission rebuild if damage occurred
issues.prevention: Monitor transmission temperatures during track use, install aftermarket transmission cooler, take cooling breaks

issues.title: Carbon Fiber Body Panel Delamination
issues.description: Some owners have reported delamination issues with carbon fiber body panels, particularly the hood and rear wing components. This appears to be related to heat exposure and manufacturing quality variations.
symptoms: Visible bubbling or lifting of carbon fiber
issues.fix_description: Panel replacement or professional carbon fiber repair and refinishing
issues.prevention: Avoid prolonged direct sunlight exposure, use car covers, regular waxing and UV protection

issues.title: Brake Pedal Feel Inconsistency
issues.description: Owners have reported inconsistent brake pedal feel, particularly after hard braking sessions or track use. The issue appears related to brake fluid boiling and air in the system.
issues.fix_description: Complete brake fluid flush with high-performance fluid, brake system bleeding, possible brake line replacement
issues.prevention: Use high-performance brake fluid, regular brake fluid changes, proper bedding procedures for new pads

issues.title: Rear Axle Steering Issues
issues.description: The rear axle steering system has been reported to develop issues with the actuators and sensors, leading to warning lights and reduced functionality of the rear wheel steering assistance.
issues.fix_description: Replace rear axle steering actuators, sensors, or control module as needed
issues.prevention: Regular alignment checks, avoid curb strikes, proper tire pressure maintenance

issues.title: Air Conditioning Compressor Failure
issues.description: Some GT2 RS owners have experienced premature air conditioning compressor failures, likely due to the extreme engine bay temperatures and vibrations from the high-performance engine.
issues.fix_description: Replace AC compressor, evacuate and recharge system, replace receiver dryer
issues.prevention: Regular AC system maintenance, avoid excessive engine bay heat exposure

issues.title: Fuel System Vapor Lock
issues.description: In extremely hot conditions or after hard driving, some owners have reported fuel system issues consistent with vapor lock, where fuel lines become too hot and fuel vaporizes, causing fuel delivery problems.
issues.fix_description: Improve fuel system cooling, replace fuel lines with insulated versions, fuel pump replacement if damaged
issues.prevention: Park in shade when possible, avoid topping off fuel tank, use high-quality fuel

issues.title: Electronic Control Unit Software Issues
issues.description: Various electronic control modules have been reported to develop software glitches, causing intermittent warning lights and system malfunctions that typically resolve with ECU resets or software updates.
issues.fix_description: ECU software updates, module reprogramming, or module replacement in severe cases
issues.prevention: Keep software updated, avoid aftermarket ECU modifications, proper battery maintenance

editorial.tagline: The most extreme 911 ever built for the street
editorial.hero_blurb: The 991 GT2 RS represents Porsche's most uncompromising vision of the 911, delivering 700 horsepower through a rear-wheel-drive chassis that demands respect. This is not merely a fast car—it's a barely-tamed race car with license plates.
editorial.essence: The GT2 RS strips away the safety net of all-wheel drive and amplifies everything that makes a 911 thrilling to its absolute maximum. With 700 horsepower sent exclusively to the rear wheels, it's the purest expression of Porsche's 'less is more' philosophy taken to its logical extreme.
editorial.heritage: The GT2 lineage began in 1995 as Porsche's answer to customers wanting the ultimate naturally aspirated 911. The 991 GT2 RS marked the triumphant return of the GT2 nameplate after a seven-year absence, incorporating lessons learned from the 918 Spyder hybrid hypercar program.
editorial.design_philosophy: Engineers pursued maximum performance through strategic subtraction—removing all-wheel drive complexity, adding aggressive aerodynamics, and implementing extensive weight-saving measures including magnesium wheels and carbon fiber bodywork to create the most focused road-legal 911 possible.
editorial.motorsport_history: While not directly raced by Porsche, the GT2 RS draws heavily from 911 RSR and GT3 Cup racing programs. Its aerodynamics, suspension geometry, and tire technology represent decades of motorsport development distilled into street-legal form.
editorial.engine_character: The twin-turbo 3.8-liter flat-six delivers explosive power with surprising linearity, building from 2,500 rpm to redline with relentless intensity. Turbo lag is virtually eliminated, creating an immediate throttle response that feels almost naturally aspirated in its urgency.
editorial.transmission_feel: The seven-speed PDK dual-clutch transmission fires off shifts with mechanical precision and brutal efficiency. Each gear change arrives with a satisfying thunk, perfectly calibrated for both track aggression and street refinement.
editorial.chassis_dynamics: The rear-wheel-drive chassis communicates every nuance of the road surface while remaining surprisingly manageable at the limit. The suspension strikes an remarkable balance between track capability and street usability, though comfort is decidedly secondary.
editorial.steering_feel: Hydraulic power steering provides intimate feedback with perfectly weighted resistance that builds naturally with cornering forces. The connection between driver inputs and front wheel response is immediate and confidence-inspiring.
editorial.brake_confidence: Massive carbon-ceramic brakes deliver devastating stopping power with exceptional pedal feel and fade resistance. The braking system instills complete confidence whether attacking apex after apex or emergency stops from triple-digit speeds.
editorial.sound_signature: The exhaust produces a sophisticated growl at idle that transforms into a ferocious roar under acceleration, punctuated by sharp pops and crackles on overrun. It's unmistakably Porsche yet uniquely aggressive in its turbocharged fury.
editorial.ideal_owner: Experienced driving enthusiasts who appreciate the purest form of performance and aren't intimidated by a car that demands skill and respect. Perfect for collectors seeking the ultimate expression of 911 engineering.
editorial.not_ideal_for: Casual drivers, those seeking daily-driver comfort, or anyone intimidated by rear-wheel-drive dynamics. The GT2 RS rewards skill and punishes complacency.
editorial.buyers_summary: Find the lowest-mileage example with complete service records and original documentation—these will appreciate significantly. Expect stratospheric running costs but incomparable driving rewards for those ready to handle 700 horsepower without electronic assistance.

expertReviews.verdict: The 991 GT2 RS remains a brutal, uncompromising supercar that delivers pure adrenaline. With 700hp going to the rear wheels only, it's a rocket ship that demands respect and skill. Despite being 6 years old, it's still faster than most modern supercars and delivers an intoxicating driving experience with incredible sound. However, it's not for inexperienced drivers - this car will punish mistakes severely.

expertReviews.verdict: The 991.2 GT2 RS represents the ultimate expression of the 911, combining brutal 700hp performance with stunning aggressive styling. While the reviewer hasn't completed the full driving assessment, initial impressions reveal a more aggressive, metallic exhaust note compared to the GT3 Touring. The car's track-focused engineering, world record Nurburgring time, and comprehensive aerodynamics make it a serious performance machine, though the high price and some interior design choices give pause.

expertReviews.title: The 991 GT2 RS is the Quickest and Fastest Porsche Road Car Ever - One Take
pros: Extremely composed and capable despite 691 horsepower
Excellent trail braking with rear steering system
Very usable as daily driver despite supercar performance
Telepathic responsiveness and handling
PCCB brakes have great feel and don't need warmup
Flat torque curve delivers power consistently
More stable than previous GT2 models due to longer wheelbase
cons: Heaviest car in the GT lineup at 3241 pounds
Requires earlier braking points due to extreme power
Very expensive with Weissach package costing $30-40k extra
Track not long enough to fully exploit the car's capabilities
expertReviews.verdict: The 991 GT2 RS delivers 691 horsepower in an surprisingly usable package that feels more like a fast road car than a race car. Despite being the heaviest GT car, it's extremely composed and won't bite unless you do something really dumb. The rear steering and PDK transmission make it accessible while the flat torque curve provides incredible performance. It's so usable that despite being rare and expensive, you'll see dozens at any Cars & Coffee.

The reviewer was impressed by its acceleration and handling precision but admits to keeping stability control on due to the car's intimidating power.

expertReviews.title: Porsche 911 GT2 RS: The Ultimate Road Review - Carfection

Excellent road manners despite track focus
Amazing sound quality
Stays composed and controllable even when sliding
Magnesium wheels save 11kg unsprung weight
Water injection system for reliability
cons: Very firm suspension on bumpy roads
Fidgety at low speeds
Weighs 400kg more than original GT1
Requires maximum concentration to drive
Expensive Weissach package adds £21k
Can be intimidating in wet conditions
expertReviews.verdict: The GT2 RS is surprisingly usable on the road despite its track-focused nature. While it demands total concentration and can be challenging on bumpy surfaces, the linear power delivery makes 690hp surprisingly manageable. It's more different from the GT3 RS in character than expected, with addictive performance that slots just behind a manual GT3 on the reviewer's personal wishlist. A hardcore road car that walks a tightrope but does so on a slightly wider rope thanks to its excellent engine.
